{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_clover_ver01/data/sn87075277/0034058059A/1958050801/0100.xml":{"full_text":"I\nI\nPage.Two\u2014B\nThe Council isn't necessarily trying to\npromote matches between the sexes. It is\nconcerned, though, with keeping people\nalive.\nA recent estimate put the U. S. popula\ntion at about 84,858,000 males and 86,371,000\nfemales\u2014about one and a half million more\ngals than guys.\n\"Men have always died at a faster rate\nthan women, perhaps largely because of the\nmore hazardous tasks they undertake and\ntheir chance-taking nature,\" the Council said.\n\"But men, especially those in the 15-24\nfige group, are dying far, far too rapidly.\"\nStatistics for a recent year turned up\nthese facts on the 15-24 age group:\nAccidents of all types take the lives of\nnearly five males for every female.\nMore than eight out of 10 persons killed\nin motor vehicle mishaps are males.\nAlmost seven out of eight persons killed\nin non-motor vehicle accidents are males.\nfiioofl Turn Day\n\u00abr\nA good turn day will be observed in\nCaldwell and community, Saturday, May 17\nand local residents are being asked to co\noperate with the Boy Scout troop under the\nleadership of Jack Bruce.\nIn conjunction with the Goodwill In\ndustries of Cambridge and Zanesville, who\nemploy only handicapped workers, the Boy\nScouts will distribute bags on Saturday, May\n10, for discarded clothing, small appliances,\ndraperies, shoes, etc.\nThey will be picked up again on Satur-\nA Mother's Svmliol\nTelephone poles long have been symbols\nof speech, supporting span by span over\nmany miles of channels of communication,\nbut there's one that stands alone on a quiet\nAmerican residential street as a symbol of\na mother's love.\nIt stands in front of a cottage which some\n30 years ago became the home of a young\ncouple. They planted ivy around the cottage.\nA son was born and grew along with the ivy.\nWhile still a small bey, he viewed the ivy in\nits abundance and transferred some of it to\nthe base of a telephone pole in front of the\nhouse. The ivy climbed the pole and draped\nitself luxuriantly over the cross-arms.\nNow the company's safety rules frown\non vines or objects of any kind on poles\nwhich telephone men must climb in main\ntaining the service but it seems that in all\nHOW RECESSIONS\nARE MADE\nBy John T. Flvnn\nPerhaps no other subject\nhas been using up so much\nprinters' ink as a thing called\nrecession. Of course, without\ne a y o u o v e n e n\nreaches into its old patent\nmedicine cabinet for the sov\nereign remedy for all colitical\nand economic ills\u2014spending\nand more spending. In obedi\nence to this urge the President\nasked Congress to authorise\nhim to borrow some more bil\nlions so he can spend us out of\nthe so-called recession. Having\nspent us into a recession with\nour billions, it is now proposed\nto spend us out of it in the\nsame way.\nPerhaps the curious reader\nmight like to know what has\ncaused the recession. There is\nnothing mysterious about it.\n\u2022It is one of the oldest of social\nills. The cause of recession is\na thing called the boom. The\nrecession is an economic dis\nease which afflicts a country\nwhen the politicians\u2014 and\nsometimes badly advised busi\nnessmen\u2014set out to create\nprosperity by creating a boom.\nAnd the standard method of\nEverybody knew Community\nHall couldn't go another season\nwithout a paint job. So Judge\nCunningham asked for volun\nteers and about a dozen people\nraised their hands.\nTrouble was most of the vol\nunteers never got around to\nworking. Weeks went by. Last\nThursday the Judge got an idea.\nHe painted the name of each\ndelinquent volunteer-in big let\nters-acro3s the part of the build\ning the man had agreed to paint.\nThat did it\u2014we'll have a fresh-\nr. pi\nEDITORIAL PAGE\nTHE^|#URNAL\n*Co'/\u00a3R.S NO*QL-\u00a3\n\u00a3OUNTy\nLlK\u00a3\nMore Males Than Females\nMore males than females are born each\nyear in the United States.\nJust why, then, are there more women\nthan men later on in life? Why the female\nsuperiority\u2014numerically, that is\u2014when it\ncomes time to find a husband?\n\"One reason,\" the National Safety Coun\ncil says, \"is because males 15-24 years of age\n\u2014the\" age when they're either thinking of\ngetting married someday or counting the\ndays till the big event\u2014are being killed in\naccidents almost five times as fast as fe\nmales.\"\nTlie Ameriean\nT-H-G.\ncreating a boom is to inspire\neither business or the govern\nment to go off on a big borrow\ning and spending spree.\nOne of these sprees followed.\nWorld War I. Borrowing and\nspending, of course, have their\nuses. But a reckless element in\nbusiness plunged headlong into\nborrowing at the banks, print\ning bond and stock issues for\nsale to the gullible public. The\nbig point to keep in mind is\nthat all this is made possible\nby printing bond and stock\nissues and selling them to in\ndividuals and groups, who in\nturn borrow on them from the\nbqnks. Thus the great circus\ngoes trumpeting along until\none day, somebody seemed to\nwake up. The banks couldn't\nlend any more the people\nwould not buy any more rail\nroad or utility or industrial\nstocks and bonds. Then folks\nbegan flooding the stock, bond\nand commodity exchanges to\nsell their stocks and bonds in\nthat wild scramble which came\nto be known as the great cash.\nIt ushered in the Great Depres\nsion, which drove the Republi\ncans out of power and put the\nDemocrats in for five terms.\nWe never got out of that\nFrom where I sit... Joe Marsh\nSuNf+Tj~N4L*\u2014\nThe young people are seven times as\nlikely to die in an accident than from cancer,\nthe No. 2 cause of death to persons in the\ncategory.\nBoth sexes are living longer today than\ntheir grandparents did, the Council noted,\nbut the so-called weaker sex has widened the\ngap-\nThirty years ago, the average white fe\nmale lived about three years longer than the\naverage white male. Today, she can expect\nto outlive her man by more than six years\nOne reason women outlive men today,\nthe Council pointed out, is because they have\nbenefited more than men from discoveries\nand innovations in the medical field.\nAnother reason suggested by the Coun\ncil They have been more careful working\nand playing than men, and technological and\nsocial changes have made women's work\neasier and safer.\n\"Regardless of what stage of life you're\nat\u2014the marriageable stage, the married\nstage of the aging stage\u2014it's smart to keep\nyour men alive,\" The Council said.\nDon't let your boyfriend or hubby over\ndo things, whether it's a minor repair job\naround the house or a long vacation drive.\n\"Make sure he keeps a light foot on the\naccelerator, and that's he's not distracted in\nto a collision by annoyances in the car or\nangered into an accident by a family spat.\n\"Keep the men alive, gals\u2014because the\nsupply isn't keeping up with the demand.\"\nday, May 17, beginning- at 9 o'clock in the\nmorning.\nAll the clothing, etc, will be turned over\nto the Goodwill Industries and the handi\ncapped workers will repair same and make\nthem like new. They will then be sold back\nto the general public.\nCaldwell residents are being asked this\nweek to be a good scout and help a Boy Scout\nand at the same time do a good turn for\nGoodwill.\nthose years there was no service trouble to\ntake a man up that pole.\nThe time came, however, when the tele\nphone company, in relocating some of its\nlines, was taking down the poles along the\nstreet. When they came to the ivy-covered\none, a woman was standing beside it. She\nwanted to keep the pole for a very special\nreason. The telephone truck moved on and\na few evenings later a representative of the\ncompany appeared before the city council\nwith a story that caused the council to pass\na special ordinance.\nNow the mother, who is a widow, can\nsit on her porch and look at her ivied symbol\nstanding alone in the treelawn, a monument\nto her son who lies in a soldier's grave some\nwhere in Italy.\nIVay\nAiSvtrtiiemtni\nShades of Tom Sawyer\npainted Hall by the weekend I\nFrom where I sit, sometime*\nwe have to be reminded of onr\nobligations. Like every so often, I\ntry and point out how important\n\"neighborly respect\" is in a com\nmunity. You may prefer soda\npop. I like an occasional cold\nglass of beer. We ought to re*\nspect each other's choice. Excuse\nme now, I've got to go help paint\nComa$uutf Hall.\nCopyright, 1958, Vnited States fyewers Foundation\nHello!\nslump until Europe went off\noh another of its crazy wars.\nIt was World War II which\nlilted us i ut of the depression\nant stmt us soaring on the\nwings of liie craziest* and gau\ndiest boom of all. And, of\nCourse, that war and post-war\nboom was created, not by pri\nvate borrowing, but by govern\nment borrowing. The national\ngovernment debt is now\nGround 280 billion dollars\u2014\nfour-fifths of it created by the\nlast war. All this money\u2014\nmoney Created by printing\nbonds\u2014is still floating around.\nBut it, and the boom it created,\nis losing its vigor. It is losing\nits vigor because all this spend\ning of borrowed money sends\n\u2022prices soaring. What is more,\nthe government bond issues\nwhich created this boom have\na way of coming due. Then the\ngovernment has to issue new\nbond issues to pay off the old\nones. At this point the govern\nment has to pay twice as much\ninterest to get its bonds sold.\nOne bond issue which carried\npercent interest had to be\npaid not long ago by issuing a\nnew bond at four percent.\nAdded to the problem of ser\nvicing the bond issues as they\ncome due, there is the ad\nditional serious phenomenon\nthat this flooding money sends\nprices skyrocketing, so that the\nmoney we get for our work\nand our goods is not worth\nwhat it once was. It won't buy\nas much as it once did. We\nmight well feel some sympathy\nfor the President who finds\nhimself trapped in this grave\nsituation. But we have to note\nthat our President, caught in\nthis frightening dilemma,\nseems unable to think of any\nthing else to do but to borrow\n(Continued on Page 3-B)\nWelirs\n\"Where Men Like\nTo Shop\"\nFRED\nMCDONALD\nWtu YOU\nCUAKE MV\nLOSSES\no\nTHE JOURNAL. CALDWELL. OHIO\nMAIL 1SAI,\nMay 1, 1958\nThe Caldwell Journal\nCaldwell, Ohio\nGentlemen:\nI am taking this opportunity to\ntell you how much we appreciat\ned your fine contribution to our\nCareer Day Program on April 9,\n1958.\nWe thank you for your time\nand effort. It could not have been\na success without you.\nSincerely yours,\nCareer Day Committee\nChairman\nE A E I A N W A Y\n3\nOne-Way Street\nFrom Journal Files\nGerald (Jerry) iiaiiisey, popu\nlar coach at the Caldwell high\nschool for the past two years,\ntendered his resignation to the\nlocal board of education this\nweek, to become effective at the\nend of the current school year,\nMay 19.\nJohn' T. Watson, 68, well\nknown resident of the Mt.\nEphraim community, east of\nCaldwell, is slowly improving at\nSwan hospital, Cambridge, from\ninjuries received Thursday morn\ning at 7:15 o'clock in a jeep-auto\ncollision on USR 21 at the south\nentrance of the Cambridge state\nhospital.\nJes S. Harris, founder and\neditor of the Noble County Lead\ner, was taken to the Memorial\nhospital, Marietta, Friday after\nnoon, wrhere he remains seri\nously ill. It is expected that he\nwill undergo surgery the latter\npart of the week.\nMiss Lena Alter left Wednes\nday for Los Angeles, Calif.,\nwhere she expects to visit for a\nmonth or six weeks.\nJOI\nTen Years Ago\nMrs. Mary Tipton\nApril 30, 1958\nThe Caldwell Business and\nProfessional Woman's club re\nceived a number of letters from\nthe students in the county and\nCaldwell schools who attended\ntheir annual Career day last\nmonth. A few of these letters\nwere selected for publication.\nTliex are as follows:\nDear Madam:\nI think your Career day was\nvery well planned and very\nEducation. I can think of no sug\ngestions for improvements.\nLarry D. Stottsberry,\nCenter Local\nDear Mrs. Mary Tipton:\nI enjoyed Career Day very\nmuch. It was a big help. After\nhearing the speakers, I have\ndecided what profession that I\nam going to take up. If Career\nDay had been held last fall for\nSophomores and Juniors, it\nwould have been an even bigger\nhelp.\nThank you for taking such an\ninterest in the Juniors and\nSeniors of Noble county. I will\nlook forward to coming next\nyear.\nLinda Montgomery,\nBeaver Local\nDear Mrs. Mary Tipton:\nI think it should be held in\nthe fall, beginning with the\nSophomore year as that is when\none begins selecting the subjects\nwhich he or she will need for a\ncareer,\nFloella Greathouse,\nBelle Vallev Local\nMr. and Mrs. Roe Jacobs have\nsold their property on Main\nstreet to Mr. and Mrs. Lewis\nMoscrip, Jr., and possession will\nbe given in the near future.\nThirty-three graduates will\nreceive their diplomas, Wednes\nday evening, May 19, when the\nsixty-second annual commence\nment is held at Caldwell high\nschool.\nJerome Schockling, 19, Cald\nwell route 4, had the la\u00a7t two\nfingers on his left hand badly\nmangled, Monday, when his hand\nslipped into an electric saw\nwhich he was operating.\nRobert Black, of Spruce\nstreet, Caldwell, is in St. Fran\ncis hospital, Cambridge, with\nhead injuries and a possible frac\ntured skull after being struck by\na tree while at work for the\nMoscrip Mining Corp., just north\nof Belle Valley, Saturday.\nA small hole was torn in the\n\"Big Inch\" pipeline belonging\nto the Texas Eastern Transmis\nsion Corp, near Hiramsburg\nMonday. The line was punctured\nwhen a coal company bulldozer\nwhich was testing for coal, ac\neidentally ran into it.\nWith approximately 54 stu\ndents of the Summerfield grade\nschool absent due to a scarlet\nfever scare, the grade school wa\nclosed Monday by county health\ncommissioner, Dr. N. S. Reed.\nOHIO\nHAPPENINGS\nunc\u2022\u2022villo At a meeting\nof the Barnesville park board\nheld at the park last Thursday\nevening, plans for the season\nwere talked over and the group\nwent over the grounds to deter\nmine needs.\nWoodsfield Thomas S\nSmith, of Kent, Ohio, has been\nemployed by the Monroe county\nSociety for Crippled Children\nand Adults to help those children\nin Monroe county who have\nspeech problems.\nWoodsfield Traffic and law\nenforcement problems arising\nfrom the increased population of\nMonroe county received atten\ntion from the Monroe county\ncommissioners, Monday.\nJefferson Sheriff's deputies\nintensified a search for thieves\nwho, last week, staged a raid\nat the Lake Erie Sports Center\nAshtabula and appropriated an\narsenal of guns.\nNew Lexington Contribu\ntions for the veterans memorial\nspeakers stand at the New Lex\ncemetery now totals $555, accord\ning to Charles Saunders, treas\nurer of the fund.\nWellington The third grade\nchildren in Mrs. Helen West\nbrooks room must have gone to\nschool this morning with great\neagerness because yesterday two\nof the eggs in the incubator in\ntheir room looked as if the baby\nchicks were picking through.\nEaton Expansion of facili\nties at the huge tower of the\nNew Hope Station on the Amer\nican Telephone and Telegraph\nCompany's radio relay expre\nway are nearing completion,\ncompany spokesman said today\nThe tower, now 190 feet high, i\nlocated west of Eaton.\nCOMPLETE AUTO SERVICE\nALL MAKES\nBARNHOUSE\nCHEVROLET COMPANY\nTelephone 261 Miller Street\nQn UJahkinqLon\nwith Rep. John Henderson\nSome functions of govern\nment are the responsibility of\nthe State others are the respon\nsibility of the Federal govern\nment. The line which divides the\ntwo is often vague and our his\ntory has demonstrated that the\nline varies from year to year.\nThere are many of us who dis\nagree upon the proper division\nbetween State responsibility and\nFederal responsibility. It was\nreadily apparent as the parade\nof Governors testified before the\nBanking and Currency Commit\ntee last week that the governors,\nthemselves, have about 40 differ\nent philosophies some who\nobject to the Federal govern\nment impressing its philosophy\nand control over what it regards\nas particularly local liberties, yet\nare requesting new and costly\nprograms of Federal assistance\n\u2014others have demonstrated that,\nregardless of whether they be\nlieve a proposed function is ol\nState or Federal nature, they are\nlocally hesitating to occupy the\nfield because of the belief that\nUncle Sam will step in. One of\nthe Governors, on specific ques\ntioning from me, admitted that,\nif the Federal government did\nnot take certain positive action,\nhe would be inclined to call a\nspecial session of his State Legis\nlature to fill the need that ex\nisted. I have found on occasion\nthat many local projects have\nbeen postponed for years because\nof the possibility that funds may\nbe available from Federal\nsources to eventually pay the\nbill. It would appear that by\nholding out a false hope that\nUncle Sam will someday do the\njob, a disservice is being rend\nered to local communities who\ncould ihave long ago commenced,\nand paid for, a much needed\nproject.\nVisitors in Washington\nNot all of the shining, whole\nsome faces tilted upward toward\nthe Capitol dome, or raised to\nsee the topmost point of the\nWashington Monument, are com\nplete strangers. Several of the\ncusters of eager students are\ngraduating classes from high\nschools in the 15th District. It\nhas become an accepted part of\nOhio's high school education that\nsome of the final days be spent\nat the nation's capital, and I\ncommend the practice, for I be\nlieve that it underlines and em\nphasi7.es to those who are about\nto under^ike the duties of citi\nzens that the historic stones and\nbeautiful shrines exemplify a\ntruly glorious republican pro\ncess.\nParadox\nGilbert and Sullivan composed\na song about a paradox for the\noperetta \"The Pirates of Pen\nzance.\" Part of the song goes\n\"We've quips and quibbles heard\nin flocks, But none to beat this\nparadox.\" While these lines\nmight have some sober applica\ntion to the current economic\nrecession, I trust that no one will\nwrite a song about the present\nparadox of continually rising\nprices, in a period of recession.\nF.very day or two I receive\na letter from someone in Ohio\nasking me why the paradox\nexists. There are probably as\nmany explanations as there are\nexperts, or those who pretend to\nbe experts. Most of them will\nagree upon one part of the dif\nficulty that we have not yet\nentered fully into the transition\nfrom the seller's market, which\nhas dominated our economy for\nthe past 15 or 20 years, to the\nbuyer's market.\nFor years, we were inclined\nto purchase what we needed at\nthe price that was demanded\nrealizing that, were we to object\nto the price, the seller could find\na market elsewhere. The time of\ntransition is here and purchaser\nhave demonstrated their stub\nbomness in the purchase of sev\neral major categories, including\nautomobiles. At the present time\nthere are a greater percentage\nof new cars being driven than\nat any other time in the Nation'\nautomotive history. As a result\nmany are content to drive their\npresent car for another year, or\neven longer, since it will provide\nthem with satisfactory transpor\ntation if the alternative is a car\nat too great a price. I intend to\ndiscuss this question in more\ndetail next week.\nNow Available!\nCTAD\nTIRES A\nAT\nHeppner's Sohio Service\nOlive Street S 78\nCOMPLETE LUBRICATION\nSERVICE\nWHEELS BALANCED\nCAR\nWASHING\nFbuoe 118J\nmm\nKOON HOLLER\nu. s. A\nGarden Time\nAt last it is garden time here in Kolon Holler. The sun is warm.\nThe winds have died down. The frost has gone out of the ground.\nThe frogs are out. The fishermen are resting along Duck Creek. The\nMartins have returned.\nThe onions are out. The radishes are sown. Vegetable Oysters\nare out as are the beets and the carrots. Early cabbage is well start\ned. Buds on the peach trees are just about ready to burst. The tulips\nare in full bloom, along with other early spring blooms.\nPotatoes have been planted, some in the moon and some in the\nfields.\nLambs are scampering all over the hills. The sheep are shorn.\nFences mended and the cattle will be in pasture May 1st, if not be\nfore.\nOats are out, wheat is doing fine and corn ground is being\nplowed.\nWho in heaven's name remembers anything about the nasty old\nwinter we had? It is as if it nevpr was. So goes life and the seasons.\nHow soon we forget.\nThis is my time of the yqjr. I love it and wish that we could\nhave eternal spring. Every spring I turn my years back one. I do\nnot add a year. That is why I will never grow old. I try to keep the\nspirit of spring in my heart and in my blood. Try it some time this\nspring and you will be surprised. Its mighty fine tonic.\nHe married Miss Bertha Mae\nRueker May 27, 1913. To this\nunion one child was born, Myrtle\nMugrage Ake, now of Bedford,\nOhio.\nHe spent his entire life on the\nold Mugrage homestead which\nwas purchased from the govern\nment by his ancestor John Mug\nrage and signed by President\nAndrew Jackson.\nTo the old homestead he added\nseveral hundred acres of land\nand was known as the most suc\ncessful sheep man in this part of\nOhio.\nHe lived a quiet and unassum\ning life, devoted to his acres and\nhis sheep and cattle.\nHe leaves a host of friends, his\nwidow and an only child Mfs.\nMyrtle Mugrage Ake\nCard of Thanks\nOur sincere thanks and grati\ntude to our many friends and\nneighbors for their expressions\nof kindness and sympathy during\nthe extended illness and death.of\nour husband and father.\nBertha Mugrage\n45 Myrtle M. Ake\nLife is a winding p-ath between\nthe swinging doors of two eter\nnities.\n2\nOne door swings and a child\nis born from eternity into life.\nAnother door swings and a soul\nis born from life into eternity.\nBetween these doors we cry\naloud for an answer to the\nmysteries of birth, life and\ndeath. There comes no answer\nsave the mocking echo of our\ncall.\nHowever in spite ipf fears,\ncreeds and dogmas in the night\nof death, hope sees a star and\nlove listening hears the rustle\nof a wing.\nA short time before Peter\nMugrage walked through the\neverlasting gate into the high\nnoon of May 1st, he whispered\nto Bertha, his faithful wife and\ncompanion, \"I hear such beauti\nful singing.\"\nToo many wrho do not under\nstand the ways of tho?e who\ntravel alone over the trails of\nnature this statement might seem\npeculiar. However to those who\nunderstood \"Pete\", as he was\nknown throughout his life, his\nstatement was as normal as the\nrising sun over hi* beloved val\nley and tumbled hills.\nPete Mugrage was a man of\nnature and Nature was his God.\nThe hills and valleys surround\ning the only home he ever knew\nwas to him a temple of the liv\ning God who spoke to him ir\neverything that grew. He Ii\"\ntened to sermons from brook\nvoices in stones, saw good ir\neverything and the simple little\nTrillium or white lily was to\nhim the Madonna of the woods\nEvery spring when the alt:u\nof Nature's Temple was newlv\ndecorated in verdant green, n\nwas his delight to pluck, a hand\nfull of these simple flowers and\ntake them to his home as if he\nhad found some precious treas\nures\u2014which indeed he had. To\nhim he saw the entire story of\ncreation, the deep mysteries of\nlife and death, laughter, sorrow\nThursday, May Hi' 1958\nUncle Sam Stille\nOBITUARY\nPeter Mugrage, son of John\nand Rhoda Brown Mugrage, was\nborn on the old Pioneer Home\nStead Feb. 6, 1873. Died on the\nold home stead where he was\nborn. May 1, 1958 at the age of\n85 years, 2 months and 25 days.\nand tears of man's existance all\nrevealed in, the simple white\npetals of this common flower.\nPete was guided by an inner\nlight which dwells in pure\nhearts, knowing that it wras said\nby the wise sages of the past\n\"Such children of spiritual wis\ndom shall see God and hear His\nvoice.\"\nHe loved the simple things of\nlife. His wants were few. While\nhe loved his acres and his sheep\nand took pride in producing one\nsingle new blade of grass and\nadding to his fold such things\nwere but the common reward of\ncommon labor. He saw in such\nincreases the unfoldment of\nnature's law.\nTo him the laws of nature's\nworld were universal in scope\nas were the laws of the spirit.\nBeing of the Unitarian and Uni\nversal school of thought it was\neasy for him to see all the mys\nteries of spiritual brotherhood\nof man and the universal con\ncept of eternal life in this\nphysical world and also in the\nspiritual existance of the higher\nlife where he now exists.\nv\nThe life of Pete, if followed\nwith understanding, should make\nthe poor rich and the common\nroyal.\nHis thoughts like bees gathered\nhoney from every blossom and\nthen with the joyous and throb\nbing heart of a child brought his\nrich booty home, to his castle of\ncontentment.\nEarly in his years, he found\nand traveled the road to Damas\ncus. From that time on he was\nguided by an inner light that\ngave him understanding and\nmade him a true child of nature.\nIn this world his needs were\nsupplied. That is why he was\ncontent to live apart from the\ncrowded highways of the world.\nTo outlive usefulness is a\ndouble death. It is a tragedy to\nlive in this life after the flame\nlacks oil. When the old oak is\nvisited in vain by spring\u2014when\nlight and rain no longer thrill\u2014\nit is not well to stand leafless,\ndesolate and alone. It is better\nfar to fall where nature softly\ncovers the once sturdy oak with\nwoven moss and creeping vine.\nLet us find consolation in the\nsoothing thought that the warm\nsouth wind\u00ab have caught up the\nsoul and spirit of our friend,\nfather and husband and have\nborn it into a realm of a new\nexistance. And so we reverently\nplace this simple little lily in\nyour empty hand as a token of\nour love and understanding\nknowing that some time we will\nmeet, and may it be some glad\nspring when the lilies bloom\nagain.\nSamtiel Harden Stille.\nmiwmrn\nElectronic Dry Cleaning\n\"If Your Clothes are Not\nBecoming to You,\nThey Should be Coming to Us-'\nREADY-MIXED CONCRETE\nSeptic Tanks\nCement-Mortar-Sand-Gravel\nSteel Mesh and Rods\nEVANS BROS. CO.\nCaldwell 13 McConnelsville 9181\nBeverly 81 Zanesville GL 31891","height":"26892","width":"21312"}}
